Preheat your oven to 220°C. Halve, then remove the cores from the @red pepper{1} and @yellow pepper{1} and cut into roughly 1cm slices. Halve, peel and finely chop the @echalion shallot{1}. Zest the @lime{1/2}. Roughly chop the @coriander{1/2}(stalks and all). Halve, deseed and finely chop the @green bullet chilli{1/2}. Drain and rinse the @mixed beans{1}(drained and rinsed) in a #colander{}.

Put the peppers on a lined #baking tray{}. Drizzle over some oil, season with @salt{} and @black pepper{} and toss to coat. Spread out evenly, then roast on the top shelf of your oven until soft and slightly crispy round the edges, ~{15%minutes}.

Place your hand flat on top of one of the @British chicken breasts{2} and slice into it from the side so it opens like a book. You've now butterflied your chicken! When all are butterflied, transfer them to a #mixing bowl{}. Add a drizzle of @olive oil{2}, a squeeze of lime juice and the @Mexican spice{1}, use this to coat the chicken.

> TIP: If you don't like it hot, go easy on the spice! Remember to wash your hands, knife and chopping board!

Put a splash of oil in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once hot, add the chicken and cook for ~{3-4%minutes} on each side. Transfer to the tray with the peppers. Roast for ~{5-6%minutes}.

> TIP: The chicken is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle. Don't wash the pan, we'll use it in the next step.

Add another splash of oil to your (now empty) frying pan and put it back on medium-high heat. Add three-quarters of the shallot. Cook for ~{2%minutes}. Add as much chilli as you dare, the mixed beans, @chicken stock pot{1/2} and @water{50}. Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Pop on a #lid{} and cook for ~{5%minutes}. Mash to a coarse paste with a #potato masher{} (or the back of a fork).

Put the remaining shallot in a #small bowl{}. Add the coriander, lime zest and olive oil. Season with salt and black pepper. Divide the beans between plates, place the chicken on top and dress with some shallot and coriander sauce. Serve your roasted peppers on the side and squeeze over a little more lime juice for good measure. Enjoy!